    explanation: `The photograph shows well-demarcated, raised, round and red-coloured lesions, some of which have coalesced. The progression pattern is another feature of the rash; it started on the extremity and subsequently involved the trunk. The visuals of the rash and the spread pattern highly suggest erythema multiforme, more so in the presence of a preceding history of a cough. Erythema multiforme is associated with various infections, antibiotics, vaccines, and chronic diseases. Erythema multiforme is a hypersensitivity reaction, causing a character in a skin rash. It is typically the result of an infection – usually from herpes simplex virus, and sometimes from mycoplasma pneumoniae. Of the options, a mycoplasma pneumoniae infection is more likely to have given rise to this clinical scenario. Mycoplasma pneumoniae is a common cause of atypical pneumonia that is often associated with extrapulmonary manifestations, including skin rashes. The cough and widespread rash in this patient strongly point to Mycoplasma pneumoniae infection, which can cause erythematous or vesicular skin eruptions, including erythema multiforme. Mycoplasma infections often present with a dry cough, malaise, and systemic symptoms. While adenovirus (option B) can cause respiratory symptoms, conjunctivitis, and gastrointestinal issues, a systemic rash is uncommon for adults. Moreover, prolonged cough is an expected feature. Option D: Legionella pneumophila causes Legionnaires' disease, which presents with pneumonia, high fever, gastrointestinal symptoms, and altered mental status. A skin rash is unusual. Option E: Rhinovirus primarily causes a common cold, typically presenting with upper respiratory tract symptoms such as runny nose and sore throat. It does not cause systemic rash. Option A: Goodpasture syndrome is a type of vasculitis characterised by pulmonary haemorrhage and glomerulonephritis. A rash is not a typical feature.`,
